description.text:
This ultra heavy adhesive tape dispenser gets its weight from a 1kg lead block inside the corpus. I got the lead from eBay as diving accessory. The body is made from 8 layers of plywood. I used a desktop cnc-machine by Stepcraft and 6 mm birch plywood.

The tape is hold by a aluminum tube which I cut to the correct length. It'd be a nice look if the tube is replaced be a complete aluminum or maybe a brass rod.

I got the knife from Opitec which is a German crafts store. It was inserted into a thin slot that was sawn by a small hacksaw after gluing the inner parts together.

To ensure the tape dispenser doesn't slip I experimented with funky foam and settled with a thin mousepad which I cut to size and fixed with double sided adhesive tape.

Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/ for more interesting designs

I used Solid Edge 2D drafting to design the side-view. Then I separated the parts and nested it as close as possible to save material. When placing the parts I took the direction of the grain into account, so that the parts side by side had alternating 'colors'

This is a very simple adjustable z-endstop holder I design for my Portabee printer.
The position of the z-endstop can be fine tuned easily with the adjustment wheel and protected by the lock switch. See instructions for more informations.

To install, carefully loosen the bolts at the back of left x-rods-clamp until the left z-bearing holder can be removed. The x-rods-clamp and x-end-motor should remain in place as shown in the last image. This case you do not need to re-install the whole x axis assembly. After installed, leave about 5mm space between the base clamp and the z-endstop holder. Locate the z-endstop holder as usual and tighten the 16mmM3 bolt. Now you can fine tune the position of the z-endstop by the adjustment wheel. Lock the position by the switch underneath after the adjustment to prevent the effect of vibrations. work with:
M3 10mm bolt x 2
M3 16mm bolt x 1
M3 nut x 3
M3 washer x 1
M3 nylon washer x 2
M4 30mm screw x 1 (optional, M4 35mm screw)
M4 nut x 3

description.text:
My latest skirmish in the never-ending battle with filament spool encroachment. These racks provide excellent storage density, pretty much doubling what you can get vs a shelf of the same depth, and they look kinda cool, too.

The shelving was bought at Lowe's, it's their "Style Selection" brand of heavy-duty double-row rails and brackets. The brackets are formed with a hollow slot facing upwards, into which the tangs on the bottom of the printed parts fit. The pipe is standard 1/2-inch black iron plumbing pipe. I bought 72-inch lengths and cut them in half for 36-inch racks. Galvanized would be fine, too, but it's twice the price of black iron.

The rear pipe holder has an extended tang which backs up against the shelving rail. The front holder doesn't have this, but you could print spacers to go between the front and rear holders to prevent the front ones from sliding backwards if necessary; so far it doesn't seem urgently needed.

If you want to get really crazy you could probably slide short pieces of plastic tubing over the pipes so that the spools could rotate and you could feed your printers straight from the rack...

Keep in mind that fully loaded, each of these racks can weigh nearly 50lbs, so screw into studs if possible, and if not, use good sheetrock anchors, use them properly, and keep an eye on them.

UPDATE 12 May 2016: I added new "clip-on" versions of the pipe supports, because having the pipes accidentally lift up out of the supports while loaded with spools is a Very Bad Thing - don't ask me how I know. The pipes snap securely into the new design - colorFabb PLA/PHA's flexibility helps here, not sure if regular PLA will work.

UPDATE 7 JULY 2016 Tinkercad link in case anyone wants to customize it:

https://tinkercad.com/things/kUUgbSo4Sgk

3/4" conduit is about 2.3mm larger in diameter than 1" iron pipe, so to convert this design to work with conduit you'll need to make the holes bigger and adjust the hole height in the support brackets for good snap-in action.

Raise N2

Notes:

The pipe holders were printed in colorFabb PLA/PHA (for its outstanding strength) on the Raise N2, and the end caps were printed in Sainsmart TPU on a Zortrax M200 with Z-Temp and ZT-HE hot end.

You could print the caps in rigid plastic, but they might need to be redesigned for a good fit. If you cut the iron pipe like I did, you can end up with threads on one end but not the other - using flex filament allows enough stretch so that the caps will fit either.

description.text:
This is the next generation of the low cost teaching microscope designed to be built and used by students to learn microscopy. Depending on your choice of lenses, this can cost between $0.40 and $3.50 per microscope. Improvements include:
  • 3D printed holder for lenses - This makes it easier for students to install them and keep their fingers off of them. I borrowed this idea from the good folks at Legoscope (http://designscience.ucsf.edu/lego/home.html)
  • Snap-together design - No glue. This version slides together into place.
  • Fewer pieces - We've reduced the number of pieces and it doesn't require a dowel anymore.
  • This version can still use disposable camera lenses but I purchased some higher quality lenses in bulk when I implemented for classroom use. (See instructions for more details)

Once again, Angi has made a great video for us at http://vimeo.com/73818990 Please Note: This version is slightly different from hers. I've removed the extra slide stand and integrated it into the comb. I've also removed the lock-ring (everyone had trouble with it) and replaced it with a clip that snaps snuggly over the end of the focus axle. I have included an illustration of how it snaps on. If you want to get the Chinese lenses we used, we got them from GS Optics (www.gsoptics.com) and ordered lens 2826, ~15mm focal length, 12.7mm diameter.
The resulting image was about 100X magnification.
An alternative is to use lenses from disposable cameras.
After playing with various options, I opted for a 3mm opening for the objective. You can hold the lens in place with a little dab of super glue. Try to keep it on the edge so that it does not affect image quality.

This is a version of The Globe Theatre I designed for a school project.

As someone that love Krosmaster (and doesn't get enough time to play it), I needed some base rings to tell my characters from my opponents. I've also seen some friends play with multiples of the same character, so these are also to help differentiate between them.

These just snap right on. The hole in the bottom makes for easy removal.

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/fyGBoC4mC3G

All those M3 nuts on the Makerbot Cupcake drive me crazy, especially the ones that are hard to reach on vertical surfaces inside things.  I wish I had something like this when I was building my cupcake.
This has a hex hole on the end that should be just about the right size for a single M3 nut.  My machine calibration might be a bit off, so the hole might be too big, let me know! The hole should be snug enough that the nut stays in a little past horizontal, but not so small that you have to press fit it.
Inside the handle is a hole that should be plenty big enough (and long enough) for the longest M3 screws in the cupcake, so not only can you hold the nut to put it in those hard to reach places, but you can screw it most of the way down even on the long screws.
Unfortunately, the ABS plastic isn't quite hard enough (or the nut socket is too big) to actually tighten the nuts down.

I've uploaded an STL file, and for those who want to modify the part, the brl-cad file.  The brl-cad file might be a bit messy, it's got several attempts in it that I might clean up later.
The bottom of the handle could use a bevel or round, but I left it flat for maximum contact with the build surface.  A few strokes of a file rounded it nicely anyway.

comments.text: I'm using a LJ12A3-4-Z/BY PNP NO inductive sensor. The sensor is powered by the 12V power supply so to lower the voltage and not blow the Ramps 1.4 board, I used a LM7805 with 0.33 and 0.1 capacitors. The signal wire (connected to Ramps 1.4) runs now at a consistent 5V when activated. The device design underwent several iterative design prototypes before the final product was settle upon. The original design was planned to be much more complex that the final product. A pin connector that contains a Zen Magnet (or any brand of 5mm spherical magnets).  
The magnets are free to spin around inside their chambers, so any pin will connect to any other. No polarity problems.

On Replicator Dual I use 10% fill, 1 shell and layer height 1.5.   
Try making a batch of pins separate. Then make your own models with the holes, and pop the magnets in. For testing, use the optional plier holes, then you can remove the pins easier if you don't like the model.  
10/02/13:  I made the plier holes optional, with the default being no plier holes. They look better. I also tightened the holeTolerance from .5 to .3, so it snaps in nice and stays put. If you want plier holes because you want to reuse your pins on different things, consider also relaxing the tolerance again.  I should have this adjust automatically but i'm on to something else already! Actually I'm considering eliminating plier holes. Feedback would be appreciated.

comments.text: Yes I changed out all the files. It was only a couple of variable assignments. They have a nice low profile now that seems just about as good as I'm going to get it. I don't intend to use other types of magnets so I did not make the zenPin customizable, but it wouldn't be too hard to do if someone chose.

description.text:
This is a holder for a battery/wireless charger (http://tinyurl.com/jzvrpgl) and my Galaxy Note 3 cell phone for on the handlebar of my bicycle. It has a retaining cover that slides down over the holder to keep the phone and battery in place while riding. There are holes in the correct places to access all the buttons and jacks on the battery and phone. Turn the keeper and clamp pieces upside down to print it without support. Use a tap to thread the threaded handlebar clamp with 8-32 threads. I used 4 @ 8-32 x 1.5" countersunk screws to hold it.

Update 9/4/2016. The treaded handlebar clamp piece broke due to strain. So, I thickened it.
Also, I purchased 2 different ones of the wifi charging battery to use with my phone and both failed very quickly. I hope the manufacturer fixes these problems.

title: IEC C8 Housing For Chinese 5v 2A Wall Wart

description.text:
Once again I bought a Tablet from Aliexpress and it came with a 2 round pin Euro type plug wall-wart and a death inducing travel adaptor (deathdaptor as Clive Mitchell would say).

Anyway, the innards of said wall-wart were not bad but the Euro plug is no use here in AU/NZ.

The photo should be self explanitory, I removed the 2 pin half of the wall-wart's shell, and replaced it with this one I designed that has an IEC C8 (figure-8/shotgun) connector and a mini switch, the switch is on the low voltage side.

The housing has a solid divider between the high voltage side and low voltage side for added safety.

Remember to play safe kids, if you don't know how to handle mains electricity, this is not the project for you.

description.text:
2016-05-20 Version 5 [added Customizer option]

This knob press fits on to a M3 wing nut. I use it on the wingnuts of a 3D printer build plate. The larger diameter of this knob makes fine leveling adjustments easier and more comfortable than using a wing nut by itself.

After installing these, I can now quickly adjust the build plate and no longer need to set a z offset in software. Movement from one digit position to the next moves the build surface 0.05 mm. More generally for ISO screws, the axial distance traveled by moving the knob from one handle cut position to next is screw pitch / numberOfCuts. M3 coarse pitch is 0.5 mm and the knob has 10 cut-outs. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_metric_screw_thread

Version 5 has default parameters to set a wingnut a little deeper into the knob. Add a M3 lock nut to the recess on the other side to keep the knob from loosening. If the wingnut opening is barely too loose or too tight, rescale the STL 0.5 % at a time to dial in the fit.

The Customizer can create knobs for other bolt sizes, but I have not tested if the wingnut cut-out proportions are effective for bolt sizes other than M3.

I have included a Simplify3D v3.0.2 Factory File to be used as a guide. Do not use it as is!

This is a remix of Sopak's Metric Screw Knob in OpenSCAD . https://github.com/brodykenrick/text_on_OpenSCAD is used to create the digits on knob.

I wanted to create a tone-generator by letting a piston move up and down on a crankshaft. Though after moving the piston through the cylinder as a test, i noticed that this way was going to make too much friction noise next to the tone sound. I have thought of a different approach for the tone-generator which i will make next.

I uploaded it here anyway for archiving purposes. If anyone wants to continue this little project feel free to do so.

Next to creating a petrol-engine (which probably will only fire 3 times before melting the PLA), you can also make a waterpump of it. Or something else innovative.

Critical parts which still have to be made: crankshaft & piston rings (in case you use it for liquid or gas)

description.text:
This is just another filament straightener, a straight filament creates less friction in the bowden tube. It also enables you to make use of those last turns of filament that are tightly coiled around the center of the spool.
To assemble you will need a 3.3mm drill and a M4 threading tool, the drill is used to clean the holes before threading. When I do the threading I soak the parts in water to give lubrication and cooling, don’t thread to fast it might cause the plastic to melt and destroy the threads. On the deep threads retract the tool when you are halfway down to remove waste before you continue the last part.
I bought the parts on eBay, I won’t update the links when they become obsolete but it’s not too hard to find similar items:

title: Slow Feeder for Cats and Small Dogs.  Prevents vomiting and overeating.

description.text:
Prolongs eating time and helps with weight control. Reduces the risk of vomiting and gas. Slower eating helps with "bloating and gulping" that can lead to vomiting in some animals. Turns your pets meal into a challenging game. Cat sized but will work for small dogs. CAUTION: Cat's are fine but monitor dogs that are very hyper and or aggressive as they may poke their own eyes.

It's hard to tell in the image but it's bowl shaped and sinks in around the center. It only holds .5-2 handfuls of food at most. Use less food for weight loss. The less food you put in the more difficult it is for them to get out and it forces them to use their paws to pull out and slowly eat each piece of food. The longer eating time of 10-30+ minutes for a cat helps them from bloating and vomiting after meals.

Printer:

QIDI TECH Dual Extruder

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.4mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The image is "very rough" first run with .4mm layer height but .2mm or .1mm could be used if you have the extra time. It's the very first print on my new QIDI Tech Dual extruder 3d printer. http://www.amazon.com/TECHNOLOGY-3DP-QDA16-01-Extruder-Structure-Filaments/dp/B01D8M32LU

I used PLA as it's environmentally friendly and plant based. 20% Infil, 4 shells, 2mm walls and ceiling. Could go much thinner as it took 8.7oz (244 grams) of filament. I have a heated bed and didn't use any rafts or supports. The first run in the picture is actually glow in the dark filament.

Sized for a 225mm x 145mm Makerbot Replicator dual clone bed but can be resized or scaled to fit your bed.

description.text:
5-14-16 Update...Added a taller bottom tray and a matching top cover. This ups the opening width to about .350in or almost 9mm...The top is a blank hex with no conditions for springs. The files are "tray runner tall", "hex blank wide1", and "drop plate tall".

Wanted to redesign a hinge for the lid on my center console of my 97 Runner. Not really possible without really altering the lid. Was checking it out and noticed some screws on the underside of the lid that would make some good mounting points for something so I whipped this up. Just a little thing to utilize some under lid storage space for documents, etc. May fit other models or years.

Two versions with multiple tops. The first model...it uses the center set of screws under the lid to hold the base and the top, it does not have a bottom (in pic). You'll need to get some longer screws and knock down the ends, #3 diameter are about the same size as the factory.

The wide version has a bottom that screws to the lid, then the top screws to that (in render pic). This widens the opening a bit. You'll need a few screws for this too setup too.

All the tops lock into the drop down plate which mounts under the hinge with the factory screws. The wide version opening is .1875in due to the base and the original is .25in. I included some springs to hold items down...the file names denote which top is setup for this.

Going to be adding some more parts soon like a taller base for a larger opening for a cellphone or whatever and some piggy-back slots to mount to the top...

title: [Parametric] proximity sensor mount for mk8 fan

description.text:
This is a proximity sensor mount for MK8 extruder fan.
The design should be adaptable to different fan and sensor sizes as well as sensor positions.

The square mount plate is attached to the fan with the 4 fan screws already available on MK8. It can be attached in front or behind the fan.
The bridge connects the plate to a circular sensor hold. The bridge is made of two perpendicular legs whose lengths can be changed individually to set the ideal offset of the sensor from the mounting plate.

My extruder's M3x40 screws were too short with this extra mount, so I used M3x50 instead; I set 10mm thickness for the mounting plate to compensate the extra thickness.

description.text: I know it's late, but why not? Just a twisted candy cane...
N/A

First - its not really beautifull, i´am really not a pro in 3D Design :-(
But good thing - it works well!

A while ago i got my hands on an airsoft ZB26 LMG, and i really liked the optic of the sights, which - like the bren guns as well - are offset to the left because the LMG has the magazine on top.

I then realized that it is really practic as well - while with normal sights you have to tilt your head over the rifle quite strange sometimes with the offset sights you basically look automatically through them when you put the gun in your shoulder.

You cant zero them in - so they are not 100% accurate of course - but they are really nice for the optic ("Hey whats that") AND they really come handy for those quick shoots around 20 meters because you can pickup your target really quick and quite decent at that range.

You will need some 3mm screws and perhaps redrill the holes, then they hold neatly and tight. Feel free to improve my design if you want ;-)

Use high infill ( 50% worked for me) for stability) and lay it flat, will print minimal support.

If you like my work and it saved you time or money, please consider supporting me on patreon or leaving my youtube channel a visit - i appreciate it!

https://www.patreon.com/MangoAirsoft

https://www.youtube.com/user/vhwie

The Mod here is of a pierced shoe to add rigidity to the design rather than the mod mentioned below.

While there are several clamps out there, I like the design of this one. This is a mostly functional modification as follows: First while the drive screw and end bar serve their primary purpose of being correct for the model, they do not hold up to any use because the layer direction is across where is should be down the length in order to eliminate support and printing undersized creates possible issues with thread to fit. In addition it was never intended to take working forces which results in massive bowing of the rails. To solve these I tapped the head stock 1/20 (be careful the PLA is very soft and will tap any direction you point, hole or not) for a piece of all-thread with a custom knob. Second I cut down a piece of 1/8 plywood to add rigidity to the bottom. At this point the weak point is the plastic thread in the head stock though it does still provide enough force for now.

title: Harlock Cosmo Dragoon ITALYmaker - full rebuilded

description.text:
Considering we wasn't able to find a good and SOLID 3D model of the mighty space gun from the Harlock saga, we decided to rebuild it all by zero: here you can find all the parts you need to print your own Cosmo Dragoon.
Please note:
1) The Cosmofront should be printed vertically, we used a Delta 2030 for that.
2) The Cosmobody needs to be printed in two specular parts (simmetry: we used the function "cut off object bottom" of CURA slicer to print it twice and than we glue it.
3) The handle needs the same: print it in two specular times, merge the part on its simmetry.
4) The parts in wood are made with the EasyWood of FormFutura and the Plug in WOOD on CURA 14.7 (it works better on the older versions).
Enjoy! :)

Notes:

All the stuff is made in simple PLA, Nozzle 0.6 Layer 0.2 WITHOUT supports.
After printing, we glue all the parts, we painted them in matt black and... That's all! :)
